  "insights": {
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "The national change is modest",
        "body": "In 2025, 4.9% of women aged 15 to 19 had experienced pregnancy, down from 5.4% in 2022. The related measures moved only slightly at the national level: 3.5% had ever had a live birth, 1.3% were currently pregnant, 0.5% had experienced pregnancy loss, and 4.8% had begun childbearing."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Regional concentration is the main divide",
        "body": "Teenage pregnancy is much more concentrated by region than the national average suggests. Zamboanga Peninsula had the highest 2025 share of teens who experienced pregnancy at 9.3%, followed by MIMAROPA and SOCCSKSARGEN at 8.2% each. At the low end, the National Capital Region was at 1.8%, the Cordillera Administrative Region at 2.7%, and Central Visayas at 3.3%."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Regional movement went in opposite directions",
        "body": "The 2025 pattern is not simply a uniform decline from 2022. SOCCSKSARGEN rose from 3.8% to 8.2%, MIMAROPA from 5.0% to 8.2%, and Zamboanga Peninsula from 7.1% to 9.3%. At the same time, Northern Mindanao fell from 10.9% to 6.4%, Davao Region from 8.2% to 4.1%, and the Cordillera Administrative Region from 6.1% to 2.7%."
      },
      {
        "heading": "High-rate regions have different profiles",
        "body": "The secondary indicators show that similar overall levels can reflect different situations. In SOCCSKSARGEN, 7.6% of teens had ever had a live birth, close to its 8.2% experienced-pregnancy rate. In MIMAROPA, the corresponding live-birth measure was 5.6% while 3.1% were currently pregnant. Negros Island Region also stands out because current pregnancy was 3.8%, higher than its 2.7% live-birth measure."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Wealth differences remain large",
        "body": "The lowest wealth quintile had the highest 2025 share of teens who experienced pregnancy at 9.4%, compared with 1.4% in the highest quintile. The same gradient appears in current pregnancy, at 3.1% in the lowest quintile and 0.1% in the highest, and in pregnancy loss, at 1.9% in the lowest quintile and 0.0% in the highest."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Lower schooling marks the sharpest subgroup gap",
        "body": "By educational attainment, teens with Grades 1-6 had the highest non-suppressed 2025 value: 17.2% had experienced pregnancy and 15.1% had ever had a live birth. The shares were much lower for Grades 7-10 at 4.7%, Grades 11-12 at 5.1%, and college at 2.6%. The no-education estimate was 7.4%, but it is based on a small 2025 count of 18 teens."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Age still matters, but the oldest teen group improved",
        "body": "The age pattern rises sharply across the teen years, from 1.5% among 15-year-olds to 9.7% among 19-year-olds in 2025. The most notable comparison with 2022 is at age 19, where the share who experienced pregnancy fell from 13.3% to 9.7%. Current pregnancy was highest at age 17 in 2025, at 2.3%, rather than among 19-year-olds."
      }
    ],
    "takeaways": [
      "Nationally, 4.9% of women aged 15 to 19 had experienced pregnancy in 2025, slightly lower than 5.4% in 2022.",
      "Zamboanga Peninsula, MIMAROPA, and SOCCSKSARGEN had the highest 2025 regional levels.",
      "The lowest wealth quintile remained far above the highest quintile, 9.4% compared with 1.4%.",
      "Regional trends diverged, with increases in SOCCSKSARGEN and MIMAROPA and declines in Northern Mindanao and Davao Region."
    ]
  }
